  "prompt": "What is the integration of \u221asinx?",
  "response": "The integral of \\(\\sqrt{\\sin x}\\) does not have a simple closed-form expression in terms of elementary functions. However, it can be expressed in terms of an elliptic integral. The integral can be written as:\n\n\\[\n\\int \\sqrt{\\sin x} \\, dx = \\int \\sin^{1/2}(x) \\, dx\n\\]\n\nThis integral can be evaluated using various methods or approximated numerically, but for exact results, we often refer to elliptic integrals.\n\nFor practical purposes, if you need this integral evaluated over a specific interval or in relation to a particular application, numerical integration techniques (like Simpson's rule or numeric integration software) may be useful. \n\nIf you have a specific limits for the integral or further context, please provide it, and I can help accordingly!",
